Seven years ago, I was working on a large optimization system.

Years of accumulated business rules.
Hundreds of thousands of lines of code.
And a user reported a small issue in production.

The fix only took two hours.

Running the test suite took much longer.

Three tests failed. They were corner cases, rare scenarios.

But ones that happened in real operations.

And that day I learned something that stuck with me: You cannot carry the full behavior of an optimization system in your head.

In Operations Research, this problem is amplified:

- Solutions are usually hard to verify visually. An incorrect solution can look perfectly reasonable at first glance. Small errors in constraint logic or data processing can lead to subtly different solutions that cost the business without ever raising an obvious red flag.
    
- Consequences are severe and costly. OR solutions directly impact critical business decisions. Errors here can translate directly into substantial, real-world costs, like stockouts, lost revenues, or significant investment losses due to flawed portfolio models.

That's why testing is not bureaucracy, but how you make optimization safe to evolve.

When tests are in place, three things happen at once:

- ‚öôÔ∏è You can refactor, tune, or swap solvers with confidence    
- üíº The business gets guarantees that key KPIs don't drift
- ü§ù Stakeholders trust the system enough to actually use it

So it provides a simultaneous thumbs-up to the three crucial players of the project.

A failing test is not bad news; it's a low-cost cue that one of these layers would have been burned later in production.

## Tools and mindset

To build your safety net effectively, we use a structured approach known as the Testing Pyramid
Start from the bottom layer and work your way up: you want fast, numerous, and isolated tests first, gradually moving toward slower, end-to-end checks.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Today, we're going to focus on the first three types of tests.

üß™ Unit tests are fast, cheap, and powerful. Use them to test things like a single constraint in isolation, a specific data pre-processing function, or a helper class.  

‚öôÔ∏è Functional tests are meant to test groups of constraints that usually form a single feature, or objective function that, in the end, needs the rest of the machinery of the model.

üèÖ Golden-case tests are specific, real scenarios you never want to break again. They usually come from bugs found in production or edge cases from real operations. Once fixed, they become tests.

1. The mindset: proactive, not reactive

When starting out, focus on these actionable steps to build the testing habit:

- Prioritize bug fixes: The easiest way to start is reactively: if you fix a bug, immediately write a test (Unit, Functional, or Golden-Case) to ensure that bug never reappears. This is a low-effort way to gain immediate confidence.
    
- Test infeasibility and invalidity: It's not enough to test what is valid and feasible. You must also write tests that confirm your model correctly reports when a scenario is infeasible or when invalid inputs are provided.
    
- Start small and isolate: Begin with unit tests for your constraints and data-handling code. Test the constraint logic in isolation before putting it into the full model.    

2. The tool: leveraging pytest In the Python OR ecosystem, pytest is the industry standard for writing robust, readable, and scalable tests.

  

- Clarity: pytest allows you to write simple functions (starting with test_ that assert expected outcomes.
    
- Fixtures: It uses powerful "fixtures" to set up complex inputs (like a full dataset or a pre-built model object) once and reuse them across multiple tests, making tests clean and efficient.
